# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sodium-sulfate-data-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] A **centimetre** (International spelling) or **centimeter** (American English), with SI symbol **cm**, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI) equal to one hundredth of a metre, *centi-* being the SI prefix for a factor of ⁠1/100⁠.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] Equivalently, there are 100 centimetres in 1 metre.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] The centimetre is the base unit of length in the now deprecated centimetre–gram–second (CGS) system of units.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] Though for many physical quantities, SI prefixes for factors of 103—like *milli-* and *kilo-*—are often preferred by technicians, the centimetre remains a practical unit of length for many everyday measurements; for instance, human height is commonly measured in centimetres.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] A centimetre is approximately the width of the fingernail of an average adult person.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] One millilitre is defined as one cubic centimetre, under the SI system of units.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/centimeter] These characters are each equal in size to one Chinese character and are typically used only with East Asian, fixed-width CJK fonts.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The **relative permittivity** (in older texts, **dielectric constant**) is the permittivity of a material expressed as a ratio with the electric permittivity of a vacuum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] A dielectric is an insulating material, and the dielectric constant of an insulator measures the ability of the insulator to store electric energy in an electrical field.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Permittivity is a material's property that affects the Coulomb force between two point charges in the material.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Relative permittivity is the factor by which the electric field between the charges is decreased relative to vacuum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Likewise, relative permittivity is the ratio of the capacitance of a capacitor using that material as a dielectric, compared with a similar capacitor that has vacuum as its dielectric.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Relative permittivity is also commonly known as the dielectric constant, a term still used but deprecated by standards organizations in engineering as well as in chemistry.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] where *ε*(*ω*) is the complex frequency-dependent permittivity of the material, and *ε*0 is the vacuum permittivity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of a medium is related to its electric susceptibility, *χ*e, as *ε*r(*ω*) = 1 + *χ*e.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In anisotropic media (such as non cubic crystals) the relative permittivity is a second rank tensor.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of a material for a frequency of zero is known as its **static relative permittivity**.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The historical term for the relative permittivity is *dielectric constant*.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] It is still commonly used, but has been deprecated by standards organizations, because of its ambiguity, as some older reports used it for the absolute permittivity *ε*.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The permittivity may be quoted either as a static property or as a frequency-dependent variant, in which case it is also known as the *dielectric function*.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] It has also been used to refer to only the real component *ε*′r of the complex-valued relative permittivity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the causal theory of waves, permittivity is a complex quantity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The imaginary part corresponds to a phase shift of the polarization **P** relative to **E** and leads to the attenuation of electromagnetic waves passing through the medium.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] By definition, the linear relative permittivity of vacuum is equal to 1, that is *ε* = *ε*0, although there are theoretical nonlinear quantum effects in vacuum that become non-negligible at high field strengths.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The following table gives some typical values.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative low frequency permittivity of ice is ~96 at −10.8 °C, falling to 3.15 at high frequency, which is independent of temperature.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] It remains in the range 3.12–3.19 for frequencies between about 1 MHz and the far infrared region.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative static permittivity, *ε*r, can be determined for static electric fields as follows: first the capacitance of a test capacitor, *C*0, is measured with vacuum between its plates.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Then, using the same capacitor and distance between its plates, the capacitance *C* with a dielectric between the plates is measured.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] For time-variant electromagnetic fields, this quantity becomes frequency-dependent.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] An indirect technique to calculate *ε*r is conversion of radio frequency S-parameter measurement results.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] A description of frequently used S-parameter conversions for determination of the frequency-dependent *ε*r of dielectrics can be found in this bibliographic source.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Alternatively, resonance based effects may be employed at fixed frequencies.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity is an essential piece of information when designing capacitors, and in other circumstances where a material might be expected to introduce capacitance into a circuit.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] If a material with a high relative permittivity is placed in an electric field, the magnitude of that field will be measurably reduced within the volume of the dielectric.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] This fact is commonly used to increase the capacitance of a particular capacitor design.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The layers beneath etched conductors in printed circuit boards (PCBs) also act as dielectrics.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Dielectrics are used in radio frequency (RF) transmission lines.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In a coaxial cable, polyethylene can be used between the center conductor and outside shield.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] It can also be placed inside waveguides to form filters.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Optical fibers are examples of *dielectric waveguides*.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] They consist of dielectric materials that are purposely doped with impurities so as to control the precise value of *ε*r within the cross-section.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] This controls the refractive index of the material and therefore also the optical modes of transmission.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] However, in these cases it is technically the relative permittivity that matters, as they are not operated in the electrostatic limit.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of air changes with temperature, humidity, and barometric pressure.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Sensors can be constructed to detect changes in capacitance caused by changes in the relative permittivity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Most of this change is due to effects of temperature and humidity as the barometric pressure is fairly stable.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Using the capacitance change, along with the measured temperature, the relative humidity can be obtained using engineering formulas.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative static permittivity of a solvent is a relative measure of its chemical polarity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] For example, water is very polar, and has a relative static permittivity of 80.10 at 20 °C while *n*-hexane is non-polar, and has a relative static permittivity of 1.89 at 20 °C.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] This information is important when designing separation, sample preparation and chromatography techniques in analytical chemistry.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The correlation should, however, be treated with caution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] For instance, dichloromethane has a value of *ε*r of 9.08 (20 °C) and is rather poorly soluble in water (13 g/L or 9.8 mL/L at 20 °C); at the same time, tetrahydrofuran has its *ε*r = 7.52 at 22 °C, but it is completely miscible with water.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the case of tetrahydrofuran, the oxygen atom can act as a hydrogen bond acceptor; whereas dichloromethane cannot form hydrogen bonds with water.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] This is even more remarkable when comparing the *ε*r values of acetic acid (6.2528) and that of iodoethane (7.6177).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] The large numerical value of *ε*r is not surprising in the second case, as the iodine atom is easily polarizable; nevertheless, this does not imply that it is polar, too (electronic polarizability prevails over the orientational one in this case).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] where *λ* is the wavelength, *c* is the speed of light in vacuum and *κ* = *μ*0*c* / 2π = 59.95849 Ω ≈ 60.0 Ω is a newly introduced constant (units ohms, or reciprocal siemens, such that *σλκ* = *ε*r remains unitless).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] Permittivity is typically associated with dielectric materials, however metals are described as having an effective permittivity, ${\tilde {\epsilon }}=\epsilon +i{\frac {\sigma }{\omega }}$ , with real relative permittivity equal to one, ( $\epsilon _{r}=1$ ).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the high-frequency region, which extends from radio frequencies to the far infrared and terahertz region, the plasma frequency of the electron gas is much greater than the electromagnetic propagation frequency, so the refractive index *n* of a metal is very nearly a purely imaginary number.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the low frequency regime, the effective relative permittivity is also almost purely imaginary: It has a very large imaginary value related to the conductivity and a comparatively insignificant real-value.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] The **dyne** (symbol: **dyn**; from Ancient Greek δύναμις*(*dúnamis*)* 'power, force') is a derived unit of force specified in the centimetre–gram–second (CGS) system of units, a predecessor of the modern SI.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] The name *dyne* was first proposed as a CGS unit of force in 1873 by a Committee of the British Association for the Advancement of Science, and is from Ancient Greek δύναμις ('force', 'power').
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] The dyne is defined as "the force required to accelerate a mass of one gram at a rate of one centimetre per second squared".
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] An equivalent definition of the dyne is "that force which, acting for one second, will produce a change of velocity of one centimetre per second in a mass of one gram".
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] One dyne is equal to 10 micronewtons, 10−5 N or to 10 nsn (nanosthenes) in the old metre–tonne–second system of units.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] The **dyne per centimetre** is a unit traditionally used to measure surface tension.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/dyne] For example, the surface tension of distilled water is 71.99 dyn/cm at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] In thermochemistry, the **enthalpy of solution** (**heat of solution** or **enthalpy of solvation**) is the enthalpy change associated with the dissolution of a substance in a solvent at constant pressure resulting in infinite dilution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The enthalpy of solution is most often expressed in kJ/mol at constant temperature.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The energy change can be regarded as being made up of three parts: the endothermic breaking of bonds within the solute and within the solvent, and the formation of attractions between the solute and the solvent.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] An ideal solution has a null enthalpy of mixing.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] For a non-ideal solution, it is an excess molar quantity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] Dissolution by most gases is exothermic.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] That is, when a gas dissolves in a liquid solvent, energy is released as heat, warming both the system (i.e. the solution) and the surroundings.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The temperature of the solution eventually decreases to match that of the surroundings.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The equilibrium, between the gas as a separate phase and the gas in solution, will by Le Châtelier's principle shift to favour the gas going into solution as the temperature is decreased (decreasing the temperature increases the solubility of a gas).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] When a saturated solution of a gas is heated, gas comes out of the solution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] Breaking solvent–solvent attractions (endothermic), for instance, that of hydrogen bonding.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] Forming solvent–solute attractions (exothermic), in solvation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] Dissolving ammonium nitrate in water is endothermic.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The energy released by the solvation of the ammonium ions and nitrate ions is less than the energy absorbed in breaking up the ammonium nitrate ionic lattice and the attractions between water molecules.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] Dissolving potassium hydroxide is exothermic, as more energy is released during solvation than is used in breaking up the solute and solvent.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The expressions of the enthalpy change of dissolution can be differential or integral, as a function of the ratio of amounts of solute-solvent.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] where ⁠ $\partial \Delta n_{i}$ ⁠ is the infinitesimal variation, or differential, of the mole number of the solute during dissolution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The integral heat of dissolution is defined as a process of obtaining a certain amount of solution with a final concentration.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The enthalpy change in this process, normalized by the mole number of solute, is evaluated as the **molar integral heat of dissolution**.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The prime heat of dissolution is the differential heat of dissolution for obtaining an infinitely diluted solution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/enthalpy-change-of-solution] The enthalpy of mixing of an ideal solution is zero by definition, but the enthalpy of dissolution of nonelectrolytes has the value of the enthalpy of fusion or vaporisation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It was long known that fires emit invisible heat; in 1681 the pioneering experimenter Edme Mariotte showed that glass, though transparent to sunlight, obstructed radiant heat.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In 1800 the astronomer Sir William Herschel discovered that infrared radiation is a type of invisible radiation in the spectrum lower in energy than red light, by means of its effect on a thermometer.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Slightly more than half of the energy from the Sun was eventually found, through Herschel's studies, to arrive on Earth in the form of infrared.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The balance between absorbed and emitted infrared radiation has an important effect on Earth's climate.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation is emitted or absorbed by molecules when changing rotational-vibrational movements.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It excites vibrational modes in a molecule through a change in the dipole moment, making it a useful frequency range for the study of these energy states for molecules of the proper symmetry.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared spectroscopy examines absorption and transmission of photons in the infrared range.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation is used in industrial, scientific, military, commercial, and medical applications.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Night-vision devices using active near-infrared illumination allow people or animals to be observed without the observer being detected.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared astronomy uses sensor-equipped telescopes to penetrate dusty regions of space such as molecular clouds, to detect objects such as planets, and to view highly red-shifted objects from the early days of the universe.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared thermal-imaging cameras are used to detect heat loss in insulated systems, to observe changing blood flow in the skin, to assist firefighting, and to detect the overheating of electrical components.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Military and civilian applications include target acquisition, surveillance, night vision, homing, and tracking.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Humans at normal body temperature radiate chiefly at wavelengths around 10 μm.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Non-military uses include thermal efficiency analysis, environmental monitoring, industrial facility inspections, detection of grow-ops, remote temperature sensing, short-range wireless communication, spectroscopy, and weather forecasting.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] There is no universally accepted definition of the range of infrared radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Typically, it is taken to extend from the nominal red edge of the visible spectrum at 780 nm to 1 mm.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This range of wavelengths corresponds to a frequency range of approximately 430 THz down to 300 GHz.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Beyond infrared is the microwave portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Increasingly, terahertz radiation is counted as part of the microwave band, not infrared, moving the band edge of infrared to 0.1 mm (3 THz).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Sunlight, at an effective temperature of 5,780 K (5,510 °C, 9,940 °F), is composed of near-thermal-spectrum radiation that is slightly more than half infrared.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] At zenith, sunlight provides an irradiance of just over 1 kW per square meter at sea level.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Of this energy, 527 W is infrared radiation, 445 W is visible light, and 32 W is ultraviolet radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Nearly all the infrared radiation in sunlight is near infrared, shorter than 4 μm.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] On the surface of Earth, at far lower temperatures than the surface of the Sun, some thermal radiation consists of infrared in the mid-infrared region, much longer than in sunlight.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Black-body, or thermal, radiation is continuous: it radiates at all wavelengths.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Of these natural thermal radiation processes, only lightning and natural fires are hot enough to produce much visible energy, and fires produce far more infrared than visible-light energy.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In general, objects emit infrared radiation across a spectrum of wavelengths, but sometimes only a limited region of the spectrum is of interest because sensors usually collect radiation only within a specific bandwidth.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermal infrared radiation also has a maximum emission wavelength, which is inversely proportional to the absolute temperature of object, in accordance with Wien's displacement law.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The infrared band is often subdivided into smaller sections, although how the IR spectrum is thereby divided varies between different areas in which IR is employed.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation is generally considered to begin with wavelengths longer than visible by the human eye.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] There is no hard wavelength limit to what is visible, as the eye's sensitivity decreases rapidly but smoothly, for wavelengths exceeding about 700 nm.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Therefore wavelengths just longer than that can be seen if they are sufficiently bright, though they may still be classified as infrared according to usual definitions.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Light from a near-IR laser may thus appear dim red and can present a hazard since it may actually carry a large amount of energy.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Even IR at wavelengths up to 1,050 nm from pulsed lasers can be seen by humans under certain conditions.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A comparison of a thermal image (top) and an ordinary photograph (bottom).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The plastic bag is mostly transparent to long-wavelength infrared, but the man's glasses are opaque.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The band comprising NIR and SWIR together is sometimes called *reflected infrared*, whereas the band comprising MWIR and LWIR is sometimes referred to as *thermal infrared*.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] These divisions are not precise and can vary depending on the publication.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The three regions are used for observation of different temperature ranges, and hence different environments in space.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The most common photometric system used in astronomy allocates capital letters to different spectral regions according to filters used; I, J, H, and K cover the near-infrared wavelengths; L, M, N, and Q refer to the mid-infrared region.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] These letters are commonly understood in reference to atmospheric windows and appear, for instance, in the titles of many papers.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Near infrared is the region closest in wavelength to the radiation detectable by the human eye.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Mid and far infrared are progressively further from the visible spectrum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] No international standards for these specifications are currently available.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The onset of infrared is defined (according to different standards) at various values typically between 700 nm and 800 nm, but the boundary between visible and infrared light is not precisely defined.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The human eye is markedly less sensitive to light above 700 nm wavelength, so longer wavelengths make insignificant contributions to scenes illuminated by common light sources.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Particularly intense near-IR light (e.g., from lasers, LEDs or bright daylight with the visible light filtered out) can be detected up to approximately 780 nm, and will be perceived as red light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Intense light sources providing wavelengths as long as 1,050 nm can be seen as a dull red glow, causing some difficulty in near-IR illumination of scenes in the dark (usually this practical problem is solved by indirect illumination).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The C-band is the dominant band for long-distance telecommunications networks.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The S and L bands are based on less well established technology, and are not as widely deployed.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation is popularly known as "heat radiation", but light and electromagnetic waves of any frequency will heat surfaces that absorb them.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared light from the Sun accounts for 49% of the heating of Earth, with the rest being caused by visible light that is absorbed then re-radiated at longer wavelengths.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Visible light or ultraviolet-emitting lasers can char paper and incandescently hot objects emit visible radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Objects at room temperature will emit radiation concentrated mostly in the 8 to 25 μm band, but this is not distinct from the emission of visible light by incandescent objects and ultraviolet by even hotter objects (see black body and Wien's displacement law).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Heat is energy in transit that flows due to a temperature difference.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Unlike heat transmitted by thermal conduction or thermal convection, thermal radiation can propagate through a vacuum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermal radiation is characterized by a particular spectrum of many wavelengths that are associated with emission from an object, due to the vibration of its molecules at a given temperature.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermal radiation can be emitted from objects at any wavelength, and at very high temperatures such radiation is associated with spectra far above the infrared, extending into visible, ultraviolet, and even X-ray regions (e.g. the solar corona).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thus, the popular association of infrared radiation with thermal radiation is only a coincidence based on typical (comparatively low) temperatures often found near the surface of planet Earth.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The concept of emissivity is important in understanding the infrared emissions of objects.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is a property of a surface that describes how its thermal emissions deviate from the ideal of a black body.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] To further explain, two objects at the same physical temperature may not show the same infrared image if they have differing emissivity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] For example, for any pre-set emissivity value, objects with higher emissivity will appear hotter, and those with a lower emissivity will appear cooler (assuming, as is often the case, that the surrounding environment is cooler than the objects being viewed).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] When an object has less than perfect emissivity, it obtains properties of reflectivity and/or transparency, and so the temperature of the surrounding environment is partially reflected by and/or transmitted through the object.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] If the object were in a hotter environment, then a lower emissivity object at the same temperature would likely appear to be hotter than a more emissive one.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] For that reason, incorrect selection of emissivity and not accounting for environmental temperatures will give inaccurate results when using infrared cameras and pyrometers.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared is used in night vision equipment when there is insufficient visible light to see.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Night vision devices operate through a process involving the conversion of ambient light photons into electrons that are then amplified by a chemical and electrical process and then converted back into visible light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared light sources can be used to augment the available ambient light for conversion by night vision devices, increasing in-the-dark visibility without actually using a visible light source.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The use of infrared light and night vision devices should not be confused with thermal imaging, which creates images based on differences in surface temperature by detecting infrared radiation (heat) that emanates from objects and their surrounding environment.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation can be used to remotely determine the temperature of objects (if the emissivity is known).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is termed thermography, or in the case of very hot objects in the NIR or visible it is termed pyrometry.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermography (thermal imaging) is mainly used in military and industrial applications but the technology is reaching the public market in the form of infrared cameras on cars due to greatly reduced production costs.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermographic cameras detect radiation in the infrared range of the electromagnetic spectrum (roughly 9,000–14,000 nm or 9–14 μm) and produce images of that radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Since infrared radiation is emitted by all objects based on their temperatures, according to the black-body radiation law, thermography makes it possible to "see" one's environment with or without visible illumination.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The amount of radiation emitted by an object increases with temperature, therefore thermography allows one to see variations in temperature (hence the name).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A hyperspectral image is a "picture" containing continuous spectrum through a wide spectral range at each pixel.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Hyperspectral imaging is gaining importance in the field of applied spectroscopy particularly with NIR, SWIR, MWIR, and LWIR spectral regions.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Typical applications include biological, mineralogical, defence, and industrial measurements.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermal infrared hyperspectral imaging can be similarly performed using a thermographic camera, with the fundamental difference that each pixel contains a full LWIR spectrum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Consequently, chemical identification of the object can be performed without a need for an external light source such as the Sun or the Moon.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Such cameras are typically applied for geological measurements, outdoor surveillance and UAV applications.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In infrared photography, infrared filters are used to capture the near-infrared spectrum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Digital cameras often use infrared blockers.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Cheaper digital cameras and camera phones have less effective filters and can view intense near infrared, appearing as a bright purple–white color.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is especially pronounced when taking pictures of subjects near IR-bright areas (such as near a lamp), where the resulting infrared interference can wash out the image.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] There is also a technique called 'T-ray' imaging, which is imaging using far-infrared or terahertz radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Lack of bright sources can make terahertz photography more challenging than most other infrared imaging techniques.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Recently T-ray imaging has been of considerable interest due to a number of new developments such as terahertz time-domain spectroscopy.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared tracking, also known as infrared homing, is a passive missile guidance system which uses the infrared emitted by a target to track it.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Missiles that use infrared seeking are often referred to as "heat-seekers" since infrared is radiated strongly by hot bodies.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Many objects, such as people, vehicle engines, and aircraft generate heat so contrast with cooler backgrounds.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared radiation can be used as a deliberate heating source.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] For example, it is used in infrared saunas to heat the occupants.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It may also be used in other heating applications, such as to remove ice from the wings of aircraft (de-icing).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared heating is also becoming more popular in industrial manufacturing processes, e.g. curing of coatings, forming of plastics, annealing, plastic welding, and print drying.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In these applications, infrared heaters replace convection ovens and contact heating.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A variety of technologies or proposed technologies take advantage of infrared emissions to cool buildings or other systems.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The LWIR (8–15 μm) region is especially useful since some radiation at these wavelengths can escape into space through the atmosphere's infrared window.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is how passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces are able to achieve sub-ambient cooling temperatures under direct solar intensity, enhancing terrestrial heat flow to outer space with zero energy consumption or pollution.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] PDRC surfaces maximize shortwave solar reflectance to lessen heat gain while maintaining strong longwave infrared (LWIR) thermal radiation heat transfer.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] When imagined on a worldwide scale, this cooling method has been proposed as a way to slow and even reverse global warming, with some estimates proposing a global surface area coverage of 1-2% to balance global heat fluxes.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] IR data transmission is also employed in short-range communication among computer peripherals and personal digital assistants.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] These devices usually conform to standards published by IrDA, the Infrared Data Association.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Remote controls and IrDA devices use infrared light-emitting diodes (LEDs) to emit infrared radiation that may be concentrated by a lens into a beam that the user aims at the detector.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The beam is modulated, i.e. switched on and off, according to a code which the receiver interprets.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Usually very-near IR is used (below 800 nm) for practical reasons.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This wavelength is efficiently detected by inexpensive silicon photodiodes, which the receiver uses to convert the detected radiation to an electric current.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] That electrical signal is passed through a high-pass filter which retains the rapid pulsations due to the IR transmitter but filters out slowly changing infrared radiation from ambient light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared communications are useful for indoor use in areas of high population density.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] IR does not penetrate walls and so does not interfere with other devices in adjoining rooms.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared is the most common way for remote controls to command appliances.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared remote control protocols like RC-5, SIRC, are used to communicate with infrared.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Free-space optical communication using infrared lasers can be a relatively inexpensive way to install a communications link in an urban area operating at up to 4 gigabit/s, compared to the cost of burying fiber optic cable, except for the radiation damage.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared lasers are used to provide the light for optical fiber communications systems.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Wavelengths around 1,330 nm (least dispersion) or 1,550 nm (best transmission) are the best choices for standard silica fibers.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] IR data transmission of audio versions of printed signs is being researched as an aid for visually impaired people through the Remote infrared audible signage project.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Transmitting IR data from one device to another is sometimes referred to as beaming.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] IR is sometimes used for assistive audio as an alternative to an audio induction loop.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared vibrational spectroscopy (see also near-infrared spectroscopy) is a technique that can be used to identify molecules by analysis of their constituent bonds.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Each chemical bond in a molecule vibrates at a frequency characteristic of that bond.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A group of atoms in a molecule (e.g., CH2) may have multiple modes of oscillation caused by the stretching and bending motions of the group as a whole.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] If an oscillation leads to a change in dipole in the molecule then it will absorb a photon that has the same frequency.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The vibrational frequencies of most molecules correspond to the frequencies of infrared light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Typically, the technique is used to study organic compounds using light radiation from the mid-infrared band, 4,000–400 cm−1.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A spectrum of all the frequencies of absorption in a sample is recorded.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This can be used to gain information about the sample composition in terms of chemical groups present and also its purity (for example, a wet sample will show a broad O-H absorption around 3200 cm−1).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The unit for expressing radiation in this application, cm−1, is the spectroscopic wavenumber.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It is the frequency divided by the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In the semiconductor industry, infrared light can be used to characterize materials such as thin films and periodic trench structures.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] By measuring the reflectance of light from the surface of a semiconductor wafer, the index of refraction (n) and the extinction Coefficient (k) can be determined via the Forouhi–Bloomer dispersion equations.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The reflectance from the infrared light can also be used to determine the critical dimension, depth, and sidewall angle of high aspect ratio trench structures.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Weather satellites equipped with scanning radiometers produce thermal or infrared images, which can then enable a trained analyst to determine cloud heights and types, to calculate land and surface water temperatures, and to locate ocean surface features.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The scanning is typically in the range 10.3–12.5 μm (IR4 and IR5 channels).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Clouds with high and cold tops, such as cyclones or cumulonimbus clouds, are often displayed as red or black, lower warmer clouds such as stratus or stratocumulus are displayed as blue or grey, with intermediate clouds shaded accordingly.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Hot land surfaces are shown as dark-grey or black.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] One disadvantage of infrared imagery is that low clouds such as stratus or fog can have a temperature similar to the surrounding land or sea surface and do not show up.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] However, using the difference in brightness of the IR4 channel (10.3–11.5 μm) and the near-infrared channel (1.58–1.64 μm), low clouds can be distinguished, producing a *fog* satellite picture.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The main advantage of infrared is that images can be produced at night, allowing a continuous sequence of weather to be studied.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] These infrared pictures can depict ocean eddies or vortices and map currents such as the Gulf Stream, which are valuable to the shipping industry.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Fishermen and farmers are interested in knowing land and water temperatures to protect their crops against frost or increase their catch from the sea.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Using color-digitized techniques, the gray-shaded thermal images can be converted to color for easier identification of desired information.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The main water vapour channel at 6.40 to 7.08 μm can be imaged by some weather satellites and shows the amount of moisture in the atmosphere.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In the field of climatology, atmospheric infrared radiation is monitored to detect trends in the energy exchange between the Earth and the atmosphere.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] These trends provide information on long-term changes in Earth's climate.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It is one of the primary parameters studied in research into global warming, together with solar radiation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] A pyrgeometer is utilized in this field of research to perform continuous outdoor measurements.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is a broadband infrared radiometer with sensitivity for infrared radiation between approximately 4.5 μm and 50 μm.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Astronomers observe objects in the infrared portion of the electromagnetic spectrum using optical components, including mirrors, lenses and solid state digital detectors.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] For this reason it is classified as part of optical astronomy.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] To form an image, the components of an infrared telescope need to be carefully shielded from heat sources, and the detectors are chilled using liquid helium.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The sensitivity of Earth-based infrared telescopes is significantly limited by water vapor in the atmosphere, which absorbs a portion of the infrared radiation arriving from space outside of selected atmospheric windows.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This limitation can be partially alleviated by placing the telescope observatory at a high altitude, or by carrying the telescope aloft with a balloon or an aircraft.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Space telescopes do not suffer from this handicap, and so outer space is considered the ideal location for infrared astronomy.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The infrared portion of the spectrum has several useful benefits for astronomers.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Cold, dark molecular clouds of gas and dust in our galaxy will glow with radiated heat as they are irradiated by imbedded stars.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared can also be used to detect protostars before they begin to emit visible light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Stars emit a smaller portion of their energy in the infrared spectrum, so nearby cool objects such as planets can be more readily detected.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared light is also useful for observing the cores of active galaxies, which are often cloaked in gas and dust.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Distant galaxies with a high redshift will have the peak portion of their spectrum shifted toward longer wavelengths, so they are more readily observed in the infrared.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared cleaning is a technique used by some motion picture film scanners, film scanners and flatbed scanners to reduce or remove the effect of dust and scratches upon the finished scan.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It works by collecting an additional infrared channel from the scan at the same position and resolution as the three visible color channels (red, green, and blue).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The infrared channel, in combination with the other channels, is used to detect the location of scratches and dust.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Once located, those defects can be corrected by scaling or replaced by inpainting.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared reflectography can be applied to paintings to reveal underlying layers in a non-destructive manner, in particular the artist's underdrawing or outline drawn as a guide.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Art conservators use the technique to examine how the visible layers of paint differ from the underdrawing or layers in between (such alterations are called pentimenti when made by the original artist).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] This is very useful information in deciding whether a painting is the prime version by the original artist or a copy, and whether it has been altered by over-enthusiastic restoration work.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] In general, the more pentimenti, the more likely a painting is to be the prime version.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] It also gives useful insights into working practices.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Reflectography often reveals the artist's use of carbon black, which shows up well in reflectograms, as long as it has not also been used in the ground underlying the whole painting.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Infrared reflectography can be realized by modified commercial digital cameras in the NIR spectral region or by dedicated instruments in the SWIR spectral region.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The recent extension of reflectography into the MWIR spectral region has proved capable of detecting subtle differences in surface materials.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Finally, NIR reflectography can be performed with good results using smartphone cameras .
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Recent progress in the design of infrared-sensitive cameras makes it possible to discover and depict not only underpaintings and pentimenti, but entire paintings that were later overpainted by the artist.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Notable examples are Picasso's *Woman Ironing* and *Blue Room*, where in both cases a portrait of a man has been made visible under the painting as it is known today.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Similar uses of infrared are made by conservators and scientists on various types of objects, especially very old written documents such as the Dead Sea Scrolls, the Roman works in the Villa of the Papyri, and the Silk Road texts found in the Dunhuang Caves.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Carbon black used in ink can show up extremely well.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The pit viper has a pair of infrared sensory pits on its head.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] There is uncertainty regarding the exact thermal sensitivity of this biological infrared detection system.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] By detecting the heat that their prey emits, crotaline and boid snakes identify and capture their prey using their IR-sensitive pit organs.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Comparably, IR-sensitive pits on the common vampire bat (*Desmodus rotundus*) aid in the identification of blood-rich regions on its warm-blooded victim.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The jewel beetle, *Melanophila acuminata*, locates forest fires via infrared pit organs, where on recently burnt trees, they deposit their eggs.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Thermoreceptors on the wings and antennae of butterflies with dark pigmentation, such *Pachliopta aristolochiae* and *Troides rhadamantus plateni*, shield them from heat damage as they sunbathe in the sun.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Additionally, it's hypothesised that thermoreceptors let bloodsucking bugs (*Triatoma infestans*) locate their warm-blooded victims by sensing their body heat.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Some fungi, like *Venturia inaequalis*, require near-infrared light for ejection.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Although near-infrared vision (780–1,000 nm) has long been deemed impossible due to noise in visual pigments, sensation of near-infrared light was reported in the common carp and in three cichlid species.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Fish use NIR to capture prey and for phototactic swimming orientation.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] NIR sensation in fish may be relevant under poor lighting conditions during twilight and in turbid surface waters.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Near-infrared light, or photobiomodulation, is used for treatment of chemotherapy-induced oral ulceration as well as wound healing.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] There is some work relating to anti-herpes virus treatment.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Research projects include work on central nervous system healing effects via cytochrome c oxidase upregulation and other possible mechanisms.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Strong infrared radiation in certain industry high-heat settings may be hazardous to the eyes, resulting in damage or blindness to the user.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Since the radiation is invisible, special IR-proof goggles must be worn in such places.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The discovery of infrared radiation is ascribed to William Herschel, the astronomer, in the early 19th century.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Herschel published his results in 1800 before the Royal Society of London.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] Herschel used a prism to refract light from the sun and detected the infrared, beyond the red part of the spectrum, through an increase in the temperature recorded on a thermometer.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] He was surprised at the result and called them "Calorific Rays".
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The term "infrared" did not appear until late 19th century.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] The Latin prefix *infra-* means below, as it is light below red on the spectrum.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/infrared] An earlier experiment in 1790 by Marc-Auguste Pictet demonstrated the reflection and focusing of radiant heat via mirrors in the absence of visible light.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The **metre** (or **meter** in US spelling; symbol: **m**) is the base unit of length in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Since 2019, the metre has been defined as the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of ⁠1/299792458⁠ of a second, where the second is defined by a hyperfine transition frequency of caesium.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The metre was originally defined in 1791 by the French National Assembly as one ten-millionth of the distance from the equator to the North Pole along a great circle through Paris, setting 10000 km as that quarter of the Earth's polar circumference.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] In 1799, the metre was redefined in terms of a prototype metre bar.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The bar used was changed in 1889, and in 1960 the metre was redefined in terms of a certain number of wavelengths of a certain emission line of krypton-86.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The current definition was adopted in 1983 and modified slightly in 2002 to clarify that the metre is a measure of proper length.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] From 1983 until 2019, the metre was formally defined as the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum in ⁠1/299792458⁠ of a second.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] After the 2019 revision of the SI, this definition was rephrased to include the definition of a second in terms of the caesium frequency Δ*ν*Cs.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] This range of uses is also found in Latin (*metior, mensura*), French (*mètre, mesure*), English (*meter* for measuring instruments, but *metre* or *meter* in poetry) and other languages.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The Greek word is derived from the Proto-Indo-European root **meh₁-* 'to measure'.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] In English, the use of the word *metre* (for the French unit *mètre*) began at least as early as 1797.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] During the French Revolution, the traditional units of measure were to be replaced by consistent measures based on natural phenomena.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] As a base unit of length, scientists had favoured the seconds pendulum (a pendulum with a half-period of one second) one century earlier, but this was rejected as it had been discovered that this length varied from place to place with local gravity.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The *mètre* was introduced, defined as one ten-millionth of the shortest distance from the North Pole to the equator passing through Paris, assuming an Earth flattening of ⁠1/334⁠.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Following the arc measurement of Delambre and Méchain, the historical French official standard of the metre was made available in the form of the *Mètre des Archives*, a platinum bar held in Paris.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] It was originally also planned to dematerialise the definition of the metre by counting the number of swings of a one-metre-long pendulum during a day at a latitude of 45°.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] However, dematerialising the definition of units of length by means of the pendulum would prove less reliable than artefacts.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The *Mètre des Archives* and its copies such as the Committee Meter were replaced from 1889 by a new standard metre made of platinum-iridium, and 29 bars calibrated against it were distributed to different nations.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] This improved standardisation involved the development of specialised measuring equipment and the definition of a reproducible temperature scale.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Progress in science finally allowed the definition of the metre to be dematerialised; thus in 1960 a new definition based on a specific number of wavelengths of light from a specific transition in krypton-86 allowed the standard to be universally available by measurement.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Where older traditional length measures are still used, they are now defined in terms of the metre – for example the yard has since 1959 officially been defined as exactly 0.9144 metre.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] SI prefixes can be used to denote decimal multiples and submultiples of the metre, as shown in the table below.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Long distances are usually expressed in km, astronomical units (149,597,871 km), light-years (63,000 au; 9.5 trillion km), or parsecs (210,000 au; 31 trillion km), rather than in Mm or larger multiples.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The terms *micron* and *millimicron* have been used instead of *micrometre* (μm) and *nanometre* (nm), respectively, but this practice is discouraged.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Within this table, "inch" and "yard" mean "international inch" and "international yard" respectively, though approximate conversions in the left column hold for both international and survey units.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] One metre is exactly equivalent to ⁠5 000/127⁠ inches and to ⁠1 250/1 143⁠ yards.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] A simple mnemonic to assist with conversion is "three 3s": 1 metre is nearly equivalent to 3 feet 3+3⁄8 inches.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The ancient Egyptian cubit was about 0.5 m (surviving rods are 523–529 mm).
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] Scottish and English definitions of the ell (2 cubits) were 941 mm (0.941 m) and 1143 mm (1.143 m) respectively.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The ancient Parisian *toise* (fathom) was slightly shorter than 2 m and was standardised at exactly 2 m in the mesures usuelles system, such that 1 m was exactly 1⁄2 toise.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/meter] The Swedish mil was 10.688 km, but was changed to 10 km when Sweden converted to metric units.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/sodium-sulfate-data-page] This page provides supplementary chemical data on **sodium sulfate**.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/sodium-sulfate-data-page] The handling of this chemical may incur notable safety precautions.
[src:sodium-sulfate-data-page/sodium-sulfate-data-page] It is highly recommend that you seek the Safety Data Sheet (SDS) for this chemical from the manufacturer and follow its directions.
